      <pb n="3"/>
      <body>
         <head>To [<persName>
                    <ptr target="../persons/pers1660">Jonathan
               Pritchard</ptr>
                </persName>]<note place="foot" n="1">For <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers1660">Jonathan Pritchard</ptr>
                    </persName>, the steward
               of the <orgName>
                        <placeName>
                            <district>Chester</district>
                        </placeName>
               society</orgName>, see <index indexName="works">
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/0001">JW</ptr>
                        </persName>'s letter to him of <date when="1753-01-16">Jan. 16, 1753</date> (<term cRef="26:499–500">26:499–500 in
                     this edn.</term>)</index>. In <date when="1757-07">July 1752</date> a <seg ana="mobs">mob</seg> had pulled down the <seg ana="MethodistPreaching-house">Methodist preaching-house</seg> in <placeName>Chester</placeName>, and the
               magistrates had been of no help. Similar <seg ana="mobs">outbreaks</seg> continued to
               occur sporadically (cf. <index indexName="works">
                        <persName>
                            <ptr target="../persons/0001">Wesley</ptr>
                        </persName>'s letter of <date when="1753-10-11">Oct. 11, 1753</date>; <term cRef="26:525">26:525 in this
                     edn.</term>)</index>, and from this letter it appears that once more the
                  <personGrp>Chester
               <personGrp>Methodists</personGrp>
                    </personGrp><!--I know we will want a "Methodists" tag (which seems most like <personGrp> to me). I wasn't sure if "Chester Methodists" merited its own <personGrp> tag, a <district> tag, or something else.-->
               were <seg ana="litigation">being denied justice by a local
            magistrate</seg>.</note>
            </head>
         <opener>
            <placeName>
               <region>London</region>
            </placeName>
            <lb/>
            <date when="1756-01-16">January 16, 1756</date>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <salute>My Dear Brother,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>If <personGrp ourBrethrenAtChester="ChesterMethodists">
                    <personGrp ourBrethren="Methodists">our brethren</personGrp> at
                     <placeName>
                        <district>Chester</district>
                    </placeName>
                </personGrp> purpose ever to
               <seg ana="litigation">prosecute</seg>, they cannot have a fairer opportunity,
            provided they have a sufficient number of witnesses whose depositions will come home to
            the point, particularly with regard to those words, <q>'You shall have no justice
               from me'</q><!--An apparent allusion to Luke 18:1-8.-->. Those depositions might
            be drawn up in the country, and sent up to <persName>
                    <ptr target="../persons/pers1117">Mr. I'Anson</ptr>
                </persName>,<note place="foot" n="2">For <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers1117">Bryan I’Anson</ptr> (d. <date when="1775">1775</date>), <occupation>a solicitor at <placeName>
                                <district>New Palace
                           Yard</district>,
                     <settlement>Westminster</settlement>
                            </placeName>
                        </occupation>
                    </persName><!--I'm not sure the <persName> tag is applied correctly, i.e., that it is bounded properly to indicate that Bryan I&apos;Anson (only) is the individual while the rest of what is contained is his <occupation>, etc.-->,
               whom <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">JW</ptr>
                    </persName> had consulted
               for <seg ana="litigation">legal advice</seg>
               <date notBefore="1760">since at least 1760</date>, see <bibl>
                        <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 5 (1906): 230–37.</bibl>
                </note> in <placeName>
                    <district>New Palace
                  Yard</district>, <settlement>Westminster</settlement>
                </placeName>. The sooner the
            better, for term will begin shortly.<note place="foot" n="3">Hilary Term for <seg ana="litigation">hearing cases</seg>
               <date from="--01-23" to="--02-13">began on Jan. 23 or 24, and ended Feb. 12 or
                  13</date>.</note> Delay does much hurt in cases of this kind. Do you hear how the
               <seg ana="mobs">
                    <placeName>
                        <region>Manchester</region>
                    </placeName> mob</seg> is
            now?</p>
         <closer>I am, <signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/>
               <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers0001">J. Wesley</ptr>
                    </persName>
            </signed>
         </closer>
         <postscript>Is <persName>
                    <ptr target="../persons/pers1475">brother Moss</ptr>
                </persName>
            gone yet into the <placeName>
                    <settlement>Birstall</settlement>
                </placeName> circuit<note place="foot" n="4">The reference may be to <persName>
                        <ptr target="../persons/pers1475">Richard Moss</ptr>
                    </persName>, an <seg ana="MethodistPreachers itinerancy">itinerant</seg> listed in the <index indexName="works">Minutes <date notBefore="1745">from at least 1745</date>
                  <term cRef="10:147">(see 10:147 in this edn.)</term>
                    </index>.</note>
            </postscript>
      </body>
